msgid "Remote Device Control"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:5
msgid "KStars provides a simple yet powerful layer for remote device control. A detailed description of the layer is described in the INDI `white paper <https://www.clearskyinstitute.com/INDI/INDI.pdf>`__."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:10
msgid "You need to configure both the server and client machines for remote control:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:13
msgid "``Server``: To prepare a device for remote control, follow the same steps in the :ref:`local/server <indi-indi-setup>` setup. When you start a device service in the ``Device Manager``, a port number is displayed under the ``Port`` column. In addition to the port number, you also need the hostname or IP address of your server."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:21
msgid "``Client``: Select the ``Tools`` → ``Devices`` → ``Device Manager...`` menu item and you can add, modify, or delete hosts into ``Client`` tab. Add a host by clicking on the ``Add`` button. Enter the hostname/IP address of the server in the ``Host``: field, and enter the port number obtained from the *server* machine in step 1."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:28
msgid "|image2|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:30
msgid "After you add a host, right click on the host to ``Connect`` or ``Disconnect``. If a connection is established, you can control the telescope from the ``Sky map`` or ``INDI Control Panel`` exactly as described in the :ref:`local/server <indi-indi-setup>` section. It is as easy at that."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:39
msgid "Running an INDI server from the command line"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:41
msgid "While KStars allows you to easily deploy an INDI server; you can launch an INDI server from the command line."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:44
msgid "Since INDI is an independent backend component, you can run an INDI server on a host without KStars. INDI can be compiled separately to run on remote hosts. Furthermore, device drivers log messages to ``stderr`` and that can be helpful in a debugging situation. The syntax for INDI server is as following:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:51
msgid "$ **indiserver** [options] driver [``driver`` ...]"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:53
msgid ""
"Options:\n"
" -l d     : Log driver messages to <d>/YYYY-MM-DD.islog\n"
" -m m     : Kill client if gets more than this many MB behind, default 128.\n"
" -d m     : Drop streaming blobs if client gets more than this many MB behind, default 5. 0 to disable.\n"
" -p p     : Alternate IP port, default 7624.\n"
" -r r     : Maximum driver restarts on error, default 10.\n"
" -f path  : Path to fifo for dynamic startup and shutdown of drivers.\n"
" -v       : Show key events, no traffic.\n"
" -vv      : -v + key message content.\n"
" -vvv     : -vv + complete xml.\n"
" driver   : Executable or [device]@host[:port]"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:67
msgid "For example, if you want to start an INDI server running an LX200 GPS driver and listening to connections on port 8000, you would run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:71
msgid "$ **indiserver** -p 8000 ``lx200gps``"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:76
msgid "Secure Remote Operation"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:78
msgid "Suppose we want to run an indiserver with INDI drivers on a remote host, ``remote_host``, and connect them to KStars running on the local machine."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:82
msgid "From the local machine log onto the remote host, ``remote_host``, by typing:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:85
msgid "$ **ssh** -L ``local_port``:``remote_host``:``remote_port``"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:87
msgid "This binds the ``local_port`` on the local machine to the ``remote_port`` on the ``remote_host``. After logging in, run indiserver on the remote host:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:91
msgid "$ **indiserver** -p ``remote_port`` [``driver``...]"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/indi-remote-control.rst:93
msgid "Back on the local machine, start KStars then open the ``Device Manager`` and add a host under the ``Client`` tab. The host should be the local host (usually 127.0.0.1) and the port number should be the ``local_port`` used in the steps above. Right-click on the host and select ``Connect`` from the popup menu. KStars will connect to the remote INDI server securely. The host information will be saved for future sessions."
msgstr ""

